Given the root node of a binary search tree (BST) and an integer key. Return the Inorder predecessor and successor of the given key from the provided BST.



Note: key will always present in given BST.



If predecessor or successor is missing then return -1.


Example 1

Input : root = [5, 2, 10, 1, 4, 7, 12] , key = 10

Output : [7, 12]


//code

/**
 * Definition for a binary tree node.
 * struct TreeNode {
 *     int data;
 *     TreeNode *left;
 *     TreeNode *right;
 *     TreeNode(int val) : data(val), left(NULL), right(NULL) {}
 * };
 */

class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> succPredBST(TreeNode* root, int key) {
        
        int pred = -1;
        int succ = -1;

        TreeNode* curr = root;

        // Find predecessor
        while(curr) {
            if(curr->data < key) {
                pred = curr->data;
                curr = curr->right;
            }
            else {
                curr = curr->left;
            }
        }

        curr = root;

        // Find successor
        while(curr) {
            if(curr->data > key) {
                succ = curr->data;
                curr = curr->left;
            }
            else {
                curr = curr->right;
            }
        }

        return {pred, succ};
    }
};

Time Complexity
Balanced BST:
O(logN)
Worst case (skewed tree):
O(N)
Space Complexity
O(1)
